{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017fSruAYhnD1zqg2dJYCHu7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KcCoqAh7Wr8fXXNvasAVoq","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Black-box verify story 8-3","prompt":"You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The `src/` directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details. If you cannot verify a feature from docs + CLI alone, that is a REAL failure in the product's documentation or packaging.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading `README.md` in the workspace at `/tmp/codeharness-verify-8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection/`. It contains install and usage instructions for the project. Use it to understand how to exercise the CLI.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file `story.md` contains the acceptance criteria you must verify. Here are the ACs:\n\n- AC1: Given a Rust project with `cargo-tarpaulin` installed, when `detectCoverageTool()` is called, then it returns `{ tool: 'cargo-tarpaulin', runCommand: 'cargo tarpaulin --out json --output-dir coverage/', reportFormat: 'tarpaulin-json' }`\n- AC2: Given a Rust workspace project (Cargo.toml contains `[workspace]`), when `detectCoverageTool()` is called, then the run command includes `--workspace` flag\n- AC3: Given a `coverage/tarpaulin-report.json` file with `\"coverage\": 85.5`, when `parseCoverageReport()` is called with format `'tarpaulin-json'`, then it returns `85.5`\n- AC4: Given `cargo test` output containing `test result: ok. 42 passed; 3 failed; 0 ignored`, when `parseTestCounts()` is called, then it returns `{ passCount: 42, failCount: 3 }`\n- AC5: Given `cargo-tarpaulin` is NOT installed, when `detectCoverageTool()` is called on a Rust project, then it returns `{ tool: 'unknown' }` with a warning\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n\n- Container name: `codeharness-verify`\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version`\n- Example: `docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness init --json`\n\nThe container has:\n- `codeharness` — the project CLI\n- `node`, `npm` — Node.js runtime\n- `curl`, `jq` — for querying observability endpoints\n\n### Project Type: Node.js CLI\n\nExecute commands inside the container and capture stdout/stderr as evidence:\n- `docker exec codeharness-verify <cli-command> [args]`\n- Capture exit codes: `docker exec codeharness-verify sh -c '<command>; echo \"EXIT:$?\"'`\n- For Node.js projects, the built artifact is installed globally in the container.\n\n### IMPORTANT: These ACs test internal library functions\n\nThe ACs reference internal functions (`detectCoverageTool`, `parseCoverageReport`, `parseTestCounts`). Since this is black-box verification with no source code, you need to exercise these through the CLI. Here's how:\n\n1. **`codeharness init --json`** likely calls `detectCoverageTool()` internally when scanning a project. Create a fake Rust project in the container with `Cargo.toml` and run init.\n2. **`codeharness coverage`** likely calls `parseCoverageReport()`. Create a fake tarpaulin report and run coverage check.\n3. For functions not directly accessible via CLI, you can use `docker exec codeharness-verify node -e \"...\"` to import and call the functions from the installed package, since `dist/` is available.\n\n### Strategy for each AC:\n\n**AC1 & AC2 & AC5 (detectCoverageTool):**\n- Create a Rust project directory in the container with `Cargo.toml`\n- For AC1: Install a fake `cargo` command that makes `cargo tarpaulin --version` succeed, then run `codeharness init --json` and check the coverage tool detection output\n- For AC2: Add `[workspace]` to Cargo.toml and check if `--workspace` flag appears\n- For AC5: Ensure `cargo tarpaulin --version` fails (no cargo/tarpaulin), then verify tool is `unknown`\n\n**AC3 (parseCoverageReport):**\n- Create `coverage/tarpaulin-report.json` with `{\"coverage\": 85.5}` in the container\n- Use node to import the coverage module from the installed package and call parseCoverageReport\n\n**AC4 (parseTestCounts):**\n- Use node to import and call parseTestCounts with cargo test output\n\n### Observability Endpoints\n\nQuery these from the HOST (not inside the container) for runtime evidence:\n- VictoriaLogs: `http://localhost:9428`\n- VictoriaMetrics: `http://localhost:8428`\n\n## Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command\n\nAfter EACH `docker exec` command you run, query the observability backend for log events:\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n```\n\nIf zero log entries, note `[OBSERVABILITY GAP]`.\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: `/tmp/codeharness-verify-8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection/verification/8-3-cargo-tarpaulin-coverage-detection-proof.md`\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n\n```markdown\n## AC N: description\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n```\n\n```output\n<actual output>\n```\n\n**Verdict: PASS/FAIL/[ESCALATE]**\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT: Only use `bash` and `output` as code fence languages.** Never use bare ``` fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. **ALL commands MUST use `docker exec codeharness-verify ...`** — do NOT run commands directly on the host filesystem.\n2. **Do NOT attempt to access source code** — there is no `src/` directory in this workspace.\n3. **Report REAL failures** — if a feature does not work, report it. Do NOT fabricate passing evidence.\n4. **Every AC needs functional evidence** — reading docs alone is not evidence.\n5. **[ESCALATE] is ONLY for things genuinely impossible to automate** — physical hardware, paid external services, human visual judgment. Infrastructure problems (missing binary, wrong version, Docker config) are NOT valid escalation reasons — report as [FAIL].\n6. **Never switch to unit-testable verification.** If Docker verification doesn't work, report WHY as a [FAIL].\n\n## Session Issues\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing problems, workarounds, risks, and observations.","subagent_type":"general-purpose"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5115,"cache_read_input_tokens":50225,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5115},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"068788d2-fa6f-4c6d-aa64-12d986e1d458","uuid":"bbc9b854-c1a2-4293-918d-0613981185d2"}
